Phase 4 (Incident Knowledge Intelligence) is fully implemented! 

Your AIOps platform now includes a full RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) pipeline. This means the AI isn't just relying on general Gemini knowledge anymore; it actually searches through your proprietary incident history and runbooks to find specific organizational context before analyzing a new error.

### What I Did
1. **Vector Database Integration**: I set up `qdrant-client` to run locally (saving embeddings into a `qdrant_data` directory).
2. **Database Models**: Added `KnowledgeDocument`, `IncidentHistory`, and `Runbook` tables to your SQLite database and ran the migrations.
3. **RAG Service API**: Created a new `/api/knowledge/ingest` endpoint that takes raw text (like a runbook or GitLab issue), translates it into a vector embedding using Google's `text-embedding-004` model, and saves it to Qdrant.
4. **Smart RCA Agent**: Updated the `rca_agent.py` to intercept the incoming error log, convert it to an embedding, perform a semantic similarity search against Qdrant, and inject the Top 5 most relevant historical incidents directly into the Gemini prompt. 
5. **Self-Learning Loop**: Every time your agent successfully generates a new Root Cause Analysis report, it will now automatically ingest its own report into the Qdrant database, making it smarter for the next identical incident!

To test this, I also ran a quick script that ingested a mock runbook for a "Database Timeout" issue detailing a fix to "Increase Hikari Pool Size from 20 to 50". 

You can read the full details in the **[Walkthrough Artifact](file:///C:/Users/vellaisa/.gemini/antigravity-ide/brain/7fb44577-5c8b-476d-aa19-ffbb5b4eb0f5/walkthrough.md)**!

Give it a try in your UI! If you trigger an RCA on a database error, you should see it intelligently pull the Hikari pool configuration fix from the runbook. What would you like to tackle next?